WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.410
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.860 --> 00:00:09.020
DIANE SHADER SMITH:
It was 1995 when

00:00:09.020 --> 00:00:13.070
the call came from the
genetic counselor telling me

00:00:13.070 --> 00:00:16.500
that our daughter, Mallory,
had cystic fibrosis.

00:00:16.500 --> 00:00:18.440
It would take a few
minutes before I

00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:21.170
came to understand that the
wailing noises that I was

00:00:21.170 --> 00:00:23.630
hearing were coming from me.

00:00:23.630 --> 00:00:27.140
At the time, Mallory was three.

00:00:27.140 --> 00:00:30.440
Soon after, we sat
with a CF specialist

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:32.689
who described what life
would be like for Mallory

00:00:32.689 --> 00:00:34.010
moving forward--

00:00:34.010 --> 00:00:37.340
the machines she would need,
the medicines she would take,

00:00:37.340 --> 00:00:39.620
the limitations she would face.

00:00:39.620 --> 00:00:43.400
He calmly told us that the
lifespan for kids with CF

00:00:43.400 --> 00:00:48.050
had changed from five to 25,
and he expected that trajectory

00:00:48.050 --> 00:00:50.200
to get even longer.

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:53.850
With that one sentence, he
introduced our new normal--

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:57.740
a childhood with
an expiration date.

00:00:57.740 --> 00:01:00.950
As I sat there bawling my
eyes out, I turned to him

00:01:00.950 --> 00:01:04.349
and asked, how do you deal with
hysterical parents and very,

00:01:04.349 --> 00:01:06.460
very sick children?

00:01:06.460 --> 00:01:10.620
His answer provided a lot
of perspective for me.

00:01:10.620 --> 00:01:12.000
He said that during
his career he

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.183
often treated kids who had been
beaten, burned, or abandoned,

00:01:17.183 --> 00:01:18.600
and that he looked
around the room

00:01:18.600 --> 00:01:22.140
and saw Mallory filled with
love and happiness, surrounded

00:01:22.140 --> 00:01:24.180
by her parents and
her grandparents,

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:28.840
and he reassured me that
she would live a happy life.

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:32.470
Before Mallory's diagnosis,
she had a lot of symptoms--

00:01:32.470 --> 00:01:35.770
a persistent cough,
a chronic runny nose,

00:01:35.770 --> 00:01:39.280
a massive bowel movements,
the first indication

00:01:39.280 --> 00:01:42.130
that gastrointestinal
problems would plague her

00:01:42.130 --> 00:01:44.490
for the rest of her life.

00:01:44.490 --> 00:01:48.030
Once Mallory started
the CF protocol,

00:01:48.030 --> 00:01:51.620
it was hard to get
her to do treatments.

00:01:51.620 --> 00:01:53.810
But the treatments
actually helped

00:01:53.810 --> 00:01:56.030
and the symptoms were abated.

00:01:56.030 --> 00:02:00.230
Specifically what she had to
do was inhale a bronchodilator,

00:02:00.230 --> 00:02:04.370
use mucus thinners, and have
chest percussion therapy,

00:02:04.370 --> 00:02:09.317
like this, to dislodge the
mucus from her chest wall.

00:02:09.317 --> 00:02:11.150
Every night, when it
was time for treatment,

00:02:11.150 --> 00:02:12.420
Mallory would hide.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:13.550
She hated it.

00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:16.250
In the closet, under
the bed, anywhere she

00:02:16.250 --> 00:02:18.470
thought we wouldn't find her.

00:02:18.470 --> 00:02:22.250
So Mark made up a game
called Astronaut and Pat Pat,

00:02:22.250 --> 00:02:25.760
Astronaut for the machine
and the swirling medicines,

00:02:25.760 --> 00:02:29.760
and Pat Pat for the
chest percussion therapy.

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:31.590
At the time, I was
desperate for a way

00:02:31.590 --> 00:02:35.520
to explain the disease to
Mallory, to her brother, Micah,

00:02:35.520 --> 00:02:38.380
and to all of our community.

00:02:38.380 --> 00:02:40.770
There was no book for
kids with CF back then,

00:02:40.770 --> 00:02:42.600
and I wanted everyone
to understand

00:02:42.600 --> 00:02:45.810
why she had to do treatment,
why she had to take pills,

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:48.630
and wine she was often
absent from school.

00:02:48.630 --> 00:02:51.150
It was terrifying
to me, so I assumed

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:52.440
it would be terrifying to her.

00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:56.840
What I did was write
a children's book

00:02:56.840 --> 00:02:59.220
called "Mallory's 65 Roses."

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:05.190
65 roses is what kids hear when
adults say cystic fibrosis.

00:03:05.190 --> 00:03:07.320
We read it to her
class every September,

00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.270
I gave it out to
all her friends,

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:11.760
and I sent it with her
when she went to camp.

00:03:11.760 --> 00:03:12.840
And it worked.

00:03:12.840 --> 00:03:15.353
Mallory led a pretty
normal childhood.

00:03:15.353 --> 00:03:16.770
Through the years,
I would give it

00:03:16.770 --> 00:03:18.510
to the boys she
would date because it

00:03:18.510 --> 00:03:21.240
was a really simple
explanation for what it was

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:24.130
that Mallory had to deal with.

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:27.670
Mallory's classmates and
her friends read the book

00:03:27.670 --> 00:03:30.040
and treated her,
throughout her childhood,

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:31.570
as if she were a regular kid.

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:33.970
And she got to play
sports, go to school,

00:03:33.970 --> 00:03:37.640
and have a very happy childhood.

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:40.370
During the years,
Mallory's medical teams

00:03:40.370 --> 00:03:42.780
became a huge part of our lives.

00:03:42.780 --> 00:03:47.270
We were lucky to have the best
of the best at Cedars, UCLA,

00:03:47.270 --> 00:03:50.270
Stanford, and UPMC.

00:03:50.270 --> 00:03:53.090
The most perceptive
doctors recognized

00:03:53.090 --> 00:03:57.200
Mallory's uncanny ability
to understand and articulate

00:03:57.200 --> 00:04:00.830
what she was dealing with
and what she had to do.

00:04:00.830 --> 00:04:03.980
And then what they did
was they used her insights

00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:07.230
to provide her with better care.

00:04:07.230 --> 00:04:11.910
Because she was so compliant,
so sweet, and so thoroughly

00:04:11.910 --> 00:04:14.100
understanding, the
doctors often asked

00:04:14.100 --> 00:04:15.870
if medical students
and residents

00:04:15.870 --> 00:04:19.029
could come to her room
for bedside training.

00:04:19.029 --> 00:04:21.010
Mallory always said yes.

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:22.900
She was always engaged.

00:04:22.900 --> 00:04:25.840
They called her the poster
child for compliance,

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.680
and they always loved her.

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:31.160
They did not always love me.

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:34.100
I was the bad cop to
Mallory's good cop.

00:04:34.100 --> 00:04:39.070
My job was to protect her even
when it made me unpopular.

00:04:39.070 --> 00:04:42.430
I was known to do a number of
different things, one of them,

00:04:42.430 --> 00:04:46.090
block the door to any person
trying to enter before 6 AM

00:04:46.090 --> 00:04:47.890
that wasn't an urgent matter.

00:04:47.890 --> 00:04:50.950
For example, somebody coming
to take out the trash,

00:04:50.950 --> 00:04:53.380
or a nursing assistant
wanting to write daily goals

00:04:53.380 --> 00:04:57.490
on the whiteboard, or
sometimes a phlebotomist

00:04:57.490 --> 00:04:59.680
wanted to come draw
routine labs, that

00:04:59.680 --> 00:05:03.650
had already been drawn
the night before, at 5 AM.

00:05:03.650 --> 00:05:06.590
Sometimes it was
a medical student,

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:08.690
very eager to please
the attending,

00:05:08.690 --> 00:05:11.030
and really just wanted to
interview Mallory, which

00:05:11.030 --> 00:05:13.130
we always said yes
to after 10:00 AM

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:16.220
but I said no to at 5:00 AM.

00:05:16.220 --> 00:05:18.110
It's different
when someone comes

00:05:18.110 --> 00:05:20.150
into the hospital for
a one-off procedure

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:23.550
or they're sick with something
that's just a happenstance.

00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:25.100
But when you have
a chronic illness

00:05:25.100 --> 00:05:27.290
and you have repeated
hospitalizations,

00:05:27.290 --> 00:05:30.860
sleep is a very critical
form of medicine,

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:34.760
and sometimes people
seem to forget.

00:05:34.760 --> 00:05:36.770
I also would sneak Mallory
out of the hospital

00:05:36.770 --> 00:05:39.560
for long walks, and one
time, arranged for somebody

00:05:39.560 --> 00:05:42.620
to pick her up and take her
to a football game for three

00:05:42.620 --> 00:05:45.500
hours between her treatments,
and then I sat by the door

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:48.320
and pretended that she was
taking a nap and blocking it.

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:53.030
You can imagine how they felt
about me when they found out.

00:05:53.030 --> 00:05:55.130
I also insisted that
Mallory keep enzymes

00:05:55.130 --> 00:05:58.280
by the bedside, which the
pharmacy wanted to control,

00:05:58.280 --> 00:06:00.950
because it's a medicine she
takes every single day at home

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:02.370
on her own.

00:06:02.370 --> 00:06:04.790
And if you don't have your
enzymes, you can't eat.

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:07.107
Friends would drop by with
ice cream that would melt.

00:06:07.107 --> 00:06:09.440
A nurse might be in the next
room with a coding patient,

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:11.930
and it would not be appropriate
for me to be demanding

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:13.220
that she get her pills.

00:06:13.220 --> 00:06:15.110
And yet I wanted to
make sure that she

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:19.040
was able to live a normal
life and be with her friends.

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:21.080
I pushed for faster
response times

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:23.870
when delays put me at risk.

00:06:23.870 --> 00:06:26.870
Now through all this, I was
supported by my husband, Mark,

00:06:26.870 --> 00:06:30.140
who was normally a very
kind and patient man.

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:32.180
His job was to fight
the insurance companies

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:35.480
to get approvals, to research
better treatment options,

00:06:35.480 --> 00:06:37.220
and to sleep
bedside in a blow up

00:06:37.220 --> 00:06:41.460
bed to make sure Mallory
was never alone at night.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:44.190
Usually kind and
patient, as I mentioned,

00:06:44.190 --> 00:06:48.090
Mark refused to tolerate errors
or mistakes, which sometimes

00:06:48.090 --> 00:06:50.460
made him unpopular too.

00:06:50.460 --> 00:06:53.100
Now all of this leads to the
first of Mallory's insights

00:06:53.100 --> 00:06:57.150
I'm going to share today, and
there will be six in total.

00:06:57.150 --> 00:07:00.780
Parents play an important
role in treating a child

00:07:00.780 --> 00:07:01.890
with chronic illness.

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:03.650
Now, that seems like
an obvious, right?

00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:05.240
Duh.

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:08.450
But what you'll find out, if you
haven't already experienced it,

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:11.180
is that sometimes,
when parents advocate

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:13.250
on behalf of their
child, it puts them

00:07:13.250 --> 00:07:16.820
at odds with both the
system or with the doctors,

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:19.380
and it leads to conflict.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:21.270
Anybody who lives in
this world will tell you

00:07:21.270 --> 00:07:22.890
that the best
collaborations come

00:07:22.890 --> 00:07:27.660
when doctors, parents, and
patients collaborate together.

00:07:27.660 --> 00:07:30.690
When Mallory was 12,
life changed again.

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:32.760
We got the call saying
that her lungs had

00:07:32.760 --> 00:07:35.910
been colonized by the
normally harmless bacteria

00:07:35.910 --> 00:07:38.500
called B. cepacia.

00:07:38.500 --> 00:07:41.740
When patients with CF get
cepacia, one of three things

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:42.520
happens.

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:46.120
The first is it turns into
a very serious illness

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:48.290
and the patient dies right away.

00:07:48.290 --> 00:07:50.620
The second, there's a
peaceful coexistence

00:07:50.620 --> 00:07:53.740
and somehow it doesn't seem
to bother the patient with CF.

00:07:53.740 --> 00:07:57.580
In the third case, it can
be a long, slow progression

00:07:57.580 --> 00:08:00.340
of disease that results
in death about 10 years

00:08:00.340 --> 00:08:03.560
after the initial colonization.

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:05.840
We tried to explain to
Mallory and to Micah

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:09.060
that things would become
a lot more difficult.

00:08:09.060 --> 00:08:11.000
This is Mallory's
brother, Micah,

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:13.940
who always was there for
her, gave her a big hug,

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:17.635
and said not to worry, that
he would always have her back.

00:08:17.635 --> 00:08:19.760
Mallory, on the other hand,
understood the severity

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:23.130
and turned to Mark and
said, am I going to die?

00:08:23.130 --> 00:08:26.700
Mark and I chose to be
honest but optimistic,

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:29.490
pragmatic but hopeful.

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:32.440
I adopted a mantra,
"No pity party."

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:35.830
The goal was to find
the joy in every day.

00:08:35.830 --> 00:08:40.807
Mallory adopted her own mantra,
which was, "Live happy."

00:08:40.807 --> 00:08:42.890
Now I want to tell you a
little bit about Mallory.

00:08:42.890 --> 00:08:46.940
She was always loving,
determined, and focused.

00:08:46.940 --> 00:08:51.230
She was tall, beautiful, and had
the longest, most perfect legs

00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:53.300
you could ever imagine.

00:08:53.300 --> 00:08:55.160
After she turned
13, there was really

00:08:55.160 --> 00:08:58.590
never a time that some
boy was not after her.

00:08:58.590 --> 00:09:01.550
She was valedictorian of her
high school, a three sport

00:09:01.550 --> 00:09:05.440
varsity athlete, and prom queen.

00:09:05.440 --> 00:09:08.740
She went on to Stanford and
graduated Phi Theta Kappa,

00:09:08.740 --> 00:09:10.870
while playing club
volleyball and participating

00:09:10.870 --> 00:09:13.780
in a lot of other
extracurricular activities.

00:09:13.780 --> 00:09:17.270
She always had friends
because she was fun-loving,

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:20.340
compassionate, and kind.

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:23.460
After college, Mallory
returned to Los Angeles

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:25.590
and moved to Manhattan
Beach with friends,

00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:27.780
where she was
surfing, socializing,

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:30.100
and working as a writer.

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:33.790
She threw herself into research
and wrote "The Gottlieb Native

00:09:33.790 --> 00:09:36.640
Garden, a California
Love Story."

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:41.190
The book was covered by AP and
got tremendous press coverage.

00:09:41.190 --> 00:09:43.290
It was the publication
of that book

00:09:43.290 --> 00:09:47.640
that enabled Mallory to envision
life as a writer, a career that

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:49.830
would be both flexible
and fulfilling,

00:09:49.830 --> 00:09:53.070
which was important because
her deep passion was

00:09:53.070 --> 00:09:56.580
environmental education,
and everybody told her

00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:00.300
that if she worked in the field,
it would expose her and put her

00:10:00.300 --> 00:10:02.930
at additional risk.

00:10:02.930 --> 00:10:05.810
But sadly, a few months
after living there,

00:10:05.810 --> 00:10:07.910
cepacia reared its
ugly head again

00:10:07.910 --> 00:10:10.070
and Mallory took a
turn for the worse,

00:10:10.070 --> 00:10:14.090
ending up in the hospital
for long stretches of time.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:16.160
While Mallory's
friends were grappling

00:10:16.160 --> 00:10:19.340
with normal,
post-college questions,

00:10:19.340 --> 00:10:23.070
Mallory had to deal with things
like IVs and indignities.

00:10:23.070 --> 00:10:23.570
Two

00:10:23.570 --> 00:10:26.480
Examples-- having
to use a bedside

00:10:26.480 --> 00:10:30.410
commode to go to the bathroom
in a glass-walled ICU room

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:34.715
when nurses were sometimes
too busy to draw the curtain.

00:10:34.715 --> 00:10:36.840
Sometimes they would come
in and they would ask her

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:39.360
about her bowel habits in front
of some new boy she had just

00:10:39.360 --> 00:10:41.490
started dating.

00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:43.760
It was horrifying to her.

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:47.790
During this period, she
was also in a lot of pain.

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:51.270
The opioid epidemic has thrown
traditional pain protocols

00:10:51.270 --> 00:10:54.670
into question and has left
many patients suffering.

00:10:54.670 --> 00:10:56.820
This was Mallory's
experience, and she

00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:59.250
writes about being victimized.

00:10:59.250 --> 00:11:01.410
During one
hospitalization, Mallory

00:11:01.410 --> 00:11:03.510
told the pain
management team that she

00:11:03.510 --> 00:11:06.780
was suffering severe pleurisy,
which is when the infection is

00:11:06.780 --> 00:11:11.488
pressed up against the lung wall
and causes excruciating pain.

00:11:11.488 --> 00:11:13.530
The dose they had given
her wasn't even beginning

00:11:13.530 --> 00:11:16.660
to address it, and when she
asked her more, they refused,

00:11:16.660 --> 00:11:20.040
saying they didn't want her
to turn into an opioid addict

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:22.920
and become ineligible
for transplant.

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:26.370
At the time, Mallory wasn't
even listed for transplant,

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:29.700
and because of the cepacia,
which is considered a superbug,

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:33.030
we weren't sure she
would ever be listed.

00:11:33.030 --> 00:11:35.610
Mallory felt their
unresponsiveness to her pain

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:38.400
was equivalent to torture.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:40.830
They also cited the fact
that another CF patient

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:42.900
down the hall had
become addicted

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:45.870
and was now not able
to get a transplant.

00:11:45.870 --> 00:11:48.390
Mallory asked her CF
team to intervene.

00:11:48.390 --> 00:11:51.280
She explained that she did
not have an addiction issue,

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:54.240
and she really just needed
better pain management.

00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:56.220
They intervened,
and she was finally

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:58.350
able to get some relief.

00:11:58.350 --> 00:12:01.290
The same scenario played
out again after transplant

00:12:01.290 --> 00:12:04.320
when they had cut her chest
open, taken out her old lungs,

00:12:04.320 --> 00:12:07.290
sewed in new lungs, and
expected her to survive

00:12:07.290 --> 00:12:09.540
on a minimal pain dose.

00:12:09.540 --> 00:12:11.970
It would take days and
days of horrible pain

00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:13.920
and suffering and
screaming before they

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:16.170
came to understand
that they had woefully

00:12:16.170 --> 00:12:19.500
under-treated her pain.

00:12:19.500 --> 00:12:22.500
Now the interesting thing is
that, at a different point

00:12:22.500 --> 00:12:25.470
in her journal, Mallory
writes about her own fears

00:12:25.470 --> 00:12:26.520
of getting addicted.

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:27.810
This is a quote.

00:12:27.810 --> 00:12:29.400
"I never thought
I would say this,

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:32.980
but I have come to love the
feeling of being on opioids.

00:12:32.980 --> 00:12:34.870
It was never part
of my treatment,

00:12:34.870 --> 00:12:37.140
but as my chest pain
became unbearable,

00:12:37.140 --> 00:12:39.090
I needed it to breathe.

00:12:39.090 --> 00:12:41.370
It also helped with my mood.

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:44.220
With morphine and with
oxy, there is no pain

00:12:44.220 --> 00:12:46.350
and there is no sadness."

00:12:46.350 --> 00:12:50.580
These anecdotes lead to insight
number two, fear of addiction

00:12:50.580 --> 00:12:52.650
must be better
balanced with need when

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:54.940
it comes to pain management.

00:12:54.940 --> 00:12:58.450
Mallory wanted to be part of an
industry-wide conversation that

00:12:58.450 --> 00:13:02.560
would address both the
opioid epidemic and the very

00:13:02.560 --> 00:13:06.220
well-documented overreaction
of well-meaning doctors

00:13:06.220 --> 00:13:09.760
and nurses who, in their attempt
to save patients from becoming

00:13:09.760 --> 00:13:13.420
addicts, under-treat pain.

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:15.470
In this era of
personalized medicine,

00:13:15.470 --> 00:13:18.850
there is no room for one
size fits all solutions.

00:13:18.850 --> 00:13:21.310
Advocating for better
pain management

00:13:21.310 --> 00:13:23.750
is part of Malory's
unfinished work

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:25.090
and part of her unfinished life.

00:13:27.990 --> 00:13:30.030
As Mallory's health
continued to decline,

00:13:30.030 --> 00:13:32.250
her Stanford doctors
asked her to move back

00:13:32.250 --> 00:13:35.490
up north so they could get
a better handle on her care.

00:13:35.490 --> 00:13:38.310
They felt that the team at
UCLA, while stellar transplant

00:13:38.310 --> 00:13:40.830
doctors and having
a great CF clinic,

00:13:40.830 --> 00:13:43.640
didn't really
understand cepacia.

00:13:43.640 --> 00:13:47.450
For a few magical months Mallory
stayed out of the hospital.

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:51.290
She went to yoga, hung out with
friends, and took long walks.

00:13:51.290 --> 00:13:53.720
It was this amazing
phenomenon and it

00:13:53.720 --> 00:13:57.050
seemed as though there had
been a dramatic quick flip

00:13:57.050 --> 00:13:59.510
of the switch.

00:13:59.510 --> 00:14:03.080
Now during this time,
Mallory looked so healthy

00:14:03.080 --> 00:14:06.140
that people didn't realize what
it was she was dealing with--

00:14:06.140 --> 00:14:09.290
67 hospitalizations
up to that point

00:14:09.290 --> 00:14:15.140
that had ranged from weeks to
months, losing friends with CF,

00:14:15.140 --> 00:14:17.390
her struggle to
prioritize her health

00:14:17.390 --> 00:14:20.310
while still trying to
keep up with her friends,

00:14:20.310 --> 00:14:21.890
the many hours
every day that she

00:14:21.890 --> 00:14:25.070
had to do treatment,
the anxiety of burdening

00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:27.200
the people that
she loved the most,

00:14:27.200 --> 00:14:32.060
and her forced
contemplation of death.

00:14:32.060 --> 00:14:34.480
It wasn't until Mallory
left for college

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:37.690
that she actually ever had to
think about how to tell people

00:14:37.690 --> 00:14:40.030
about her invisible illness.

00:14:40.030 --> 00:14:42.160
But dorm living has
a way of establishing

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:44.830
immediate intimacy, and
word spread quickly,

00:14:44.830 --> 00:14:48.220
which relieved her of the
burden of having to disclose.

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:50.560
But after college,
the issue came up

00:14:50.560 --> 00:14:54.340
with Jack, her real
life Prince Charming.

00:14:54.340 --> 00:14:57.070
Mallory met Jack
on New Year's Eve.

00:14:57.070 --> 00:14:59.920
She had just gotten out of
the hospital and was on IVs.

00:14:59.920 --> 00:15:02.680
She thought Jack was
super cute and very nice,

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:05.530
but he lived in Palo
Alto and she lived in LA,

00:15:05.530 --> 00:15:07.690
and she knew that with
her health condition

00:15:07.690 --> 00:15:10.160
she could not manage a
long distance relationship.

00:15:10.160 --> 00:15:12.520
So she never really gave
him a second thought.

00:15:12.520 --> 00:15:15.710
But months later, when Malory
did move back up north,

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:17.800
they re-met at a party.

00:15:17.800 --> 00:15:19.600
They were playing
a game together

00:15:19.600 --> 00:15:22.500
when she felt a bout of
hemoptysis coming on.

00:15:22.500 --> 00:15:24.910
Hemopytsis is when
you cough up blood,

00:15:24.910 --> 00:15:29.020
and it can be a 911
deadly emergency.

00:15:29.020 --> 00:15:31.300
When she came out
of the bathroom,

00:15:31.300 --> 00:15:35.530
Jack expressed concern, which
leads to insight number three.

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:38.260
It's sometimes difficult
to know when to disclose

00:15:38.260 --> 00:15:40.240
an invisible illness.

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:43.990
Mallory often said that
the issue of disclosure

00:15:43.990 --> 00:15:46.270
was one of the hardest
things about having

00:15:46.270 --> 00:15:47.680
an invisible illness.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:49.900
She worried about
burdening new friends,

00:15:49.900 --> 00:15:52.840
and worried about scaring
off potential employers.

00:15:52.840 --> 00:15:55.060
And in one very
specific example,

00:15:55.060 --> 00:15:57.100
Mallory applied
for a writing job,

00:15:57.100 --> 00:15:59.650
spent two weeks
perfecting her samples,

00:15:59.650 --> 00:16:03.100
turned them in, was told
they were fantastic,

00:16:03.100 --> 00:16:05.710
was offered a job,
and when she told me

00:16:05.710 --> 00:16:07.360
she was going to
start the next week,

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:09.610
I told her that
she needed to let

00:16:09.610 --> 00:16:13.930
them know that she had a
disease that might render her

00:16:13.930 --> 00:16:15.700
unable to come into the office.

00:16:15.700 --> 00:16:19.320
When she told them, suddenly
it wasn't a good fit

00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:22.800
and the offer was reneged.

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:25.710
Mallory also feared that no
man would love her enough

00:16:25.710 --> 00:16:28.850
to accept the complications
of her disease,

00:16:28.850 --> 00:16:30.860
so she often wrestled
with the decision

00:16:30.860 --> 00:16:33.860
about whether or not to tell
the people that she was dating.

00:16:33.860 --> 00:16:37.680
But with Jack, she felt that
there was something special

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:40.190
and she wanted him
to know right away.

00:16:40.190 --> 00:16:42.830
She did come to the
conclusion that, in terms

00:16:42.830 --> 00:16:46.800
of right and wrong, there
isn't really a correct answer.

00:16:46.800 --> 00:16:49.640
But with Jack, because
she felt something,

00:16:49.640 --> 00:16:52.040
she wanted him to know
right from the start what

00:16:52.040 --> 00:16:54.890
he was getting into,
and she asked herself,

00:16:54.890 --> 00:16:57.170
is this man who's
there for me when

00:16:57.170 --> 00:17:00.000
I'm laughing and partying
going to be there for me when

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:00.875
I'm sick and sedated?

00:17:03.920 --> 00:17:06.319
It was a good thing that
Mallory told Jack right away,

00:17:06.319 --> 00:17:09.420
because very soon after, she
ended up back in the hospital,

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:13.390
and it the first of many
more admissions to come.

00:17:13.390 --> 00:17:15.280
Over the next few
months, the antibiotics

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:17.680
seemed to stop
working and Mallory

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:19.569
was inching closer
to the time when

00:17:19.569 --> 00:17:21.560
she would need a transplant.

00:17:21.560 --> 00:17:24.040
The only center in the
country that would accept her,

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:26.230
because of the
cepacia, was University

00:17:26.230 --> 00:17:30.620
of Pittsburgh
Medical Center, UPMC.

00:17:30.620 --> 00:17:34.770
They asked us to come in
for a week-long evaluation,

00:17:34.770 --> 00:17:36.840
and when we said,
great, anytime,

00:17:36.840 --> 00:17:39.750
tell us when, they explained
that the difficulty would

00:17:39.750 --> 00:17:42.285
be getting our insurance
company to say yes.

00:17:42.285 --> 00:17:44.160
And I said, that's not
going to be a problem.

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:45.040
Mark went to Harvard.

00:17:45.040 --> 00:17:45.870
He's a lawyer.

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:46.710
I'm a publicist.

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:49.360
I'll go on the Today Show
if they try to deny it.

00:17:49.360 --> 00:17:51.130
But guess what?

00:17:51.130 --> 00:17:52.810
They said no.

00:17:52.810 --> 00:17:55.990
Getting insurance approval for
an out-of-state, out-of-network

00:17:55.990 --> 00:17:59.710
hospital was the single
hardest and most excruciating

00:17:59.710 --> 00:18:03.360
non-medical challenge
that we faced.

00:18:03.360 --> 00:18:05.460
The battle raged on for weeks.

00:18:05.460 --> 00:18:07.950
They employed multiple stall
tactics that Mallory felt

00:18:07.950 --> 00:18:10.980
were intended to run the
clock out on her life.

00:18:10.980 --> 00:18:15.150
It would absolutely take a
miracle to turn no into yes.

00:18:15.150 --> 00:18:17.130
But in Mallory's
case, the miracle

00:18:17.130 --> 00:18:20.760
came in the form of a very
close friend with connections

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:24.900
to the highest level of
insurance company's management.

00:18:24.900 --> 00:18:27.660
Mallory knew she was
incredibly lucky,

00:18:27.660 --> 00:18:31.170
but she understood that
not everybody would be.

00:18:31.170 --> 00:18:34.740
She documents this journey
in "Salt in my Soul"

00:18:34.740 --> 00:18:37.710
because she wants others to
see exactly what happened

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:41.370
and how she attempted
to resolve it.

00:18:41.370 --> 00:18:43.740
Insurance companies
often inflict

00:18:43.740 --> 00:18:46.530
needless additional suffering
on patients who are already

00:18:46.530 --> 00:18:48.990
in pain and already at stress.

00:18:48.990 --> 00:18:52.380
It's outrageous and
incomprehensible,

00:18:52.380 --> 00:18:56.880
which leads to insight number
four, that doctors, not

00:18:56.880 --> 00:18:59.340
insurance company or
insurance company doctors,

00:18:59.340 --> 00:19:02.850
should decide who gets
care and where they get it,

00:19:02.850 --> 00:19:06.150
and what coverage is allowed.

00:19:06.150 --> 00:19:08.452
Mallory and I spent a
grueling week in Pittsburgh,

00:19:08.452 --> 00:19:10.410
and the reason I say
grueling is that, in order

00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:12.142
to be accepted for
transplant, you

00:19:12.142 --> 00:19:14.100
have to meet with a number
of different teams--

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:17.700
surgeons, case managers,
financial advisors,

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:18.960
pharmacists.

00:19:18.960 --> 00:19:20.100
The list goes on and on.

00:19:20.100 --> 00:19:22.740
They want to make sure you
are physically strong enough,

00:19:22.740 --> 00:19:24.240
emotionally strong
enough, that you

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:25.860
have the financial
resources to be

00:19:25.860 --> 00:19:28.742
able to cover the expenses
that will inevitably come up,

00:19:28.742 --> 00:19:31.200
and they want to make sure that
you have two support-givers

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:34.180
with you at all times.

00:19:34.180 --> 00:19:36.700
We left Pittsburgh after that
week on pins and needles,

00:19:36.700 --> 00:19:39.670
but hopeful, because they
seem pretty optimistic,

00:19:39.670 --> 00:19:44.470
and on Mallory's 24th
birthday, October 12th of 2016,

00:19:44.470 --> 00:19:47.410
the call came in saying
that UPMC was accepting her

00:19:47.410 --> 00:19:48.610
for transplant.

00:19:48.610 --> 00:19:51.190
But at that point, they said
she was too healthy to come,

00:19:51.190 --> 00:19:52.750
which was quite
amazing considering

00:19:52.750 --> 00:19:54.190
how sick she'd been.

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:56.950
But of course, shortly after
that, as it always happened,

00:19:56.950 --> 00:19:59.920
she got mono and the flu
and ended up very sick,

00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:02.350
back at UCLA Hospital-- we
brought her home to make sure

00:20:02.350 --> 00:20:04.120
we could provide full support--

00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:08.140
while we were waiting for them
to tell us it was time to come.

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:11.110
During that period, she got
so sick that at one point,

00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:13.000
UPMC said it might
not make sense

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.820
to come if you're just
going to come here to die.

00:20:15.820 --> 00:20:18.727
So we had to wait until
she was physically stable,

00:20:18.727 --> 00:20:20.560
and then we could get
her across the country

00:20:20.560 --> 00:20:22.150
for this grueling move.

00:20:22.150 --> 00:20:24.700
Eventually, in February,
the call came on a Monday

00:20:24.700 --> 00:20:27.490
with instructions to
be in clinic on Friday,

00:20:27.490 --> 00:20:28.930
and to fly on Thursday.

00:20:28.930 --> 00:20:31.780
So we had two days
to pack everything up

00:20:31.780 --> 00:20:34.180
and say goodbye to the
people that she knew

00:20:34.180 --> 00:20:36.010
she might not come back to.

00:20:36.010 --> 00:20:39.040
She was most sad about
leaving her dog, Kona,

00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:42.450
who was too big to
make the trip with us.

00:20:42.450 --> 00:20:45.810
After a lot of upheaval, we
hunkered down in Pittsburgh

00:20:45.810 --> 00:20:47.490
waiting for the call.

00:20:47.490 --> 00:20:50.520
To a patient with end-stage
lung disease that's

00:20:50.520 --> 00:20:53.790
listed for transplant, the
single most important thing

00:20:53.790 --> 00:20:57.340
to do is wait for that call.

00:20:57.340 --> 00:20:59.920
You can't go to the
movies, take a shower,

00:20:59.920 --> 00:21:02.277
sleep through the night,
do anything without having

00:21:02.277 --> 00:21:04.360
your phone tethered to you
because you cannot miss

00:21:04.360 --> 00:21:07.440
a single call.

00:21:07.440 --> 00:21:10.610
But what happens is, the
heightened vigilance starts

00:21:10.610 --> 00:21:13.520
to give way to hopelessness
as days and weeks pass

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:15.830
and you start to think
the call will never come,

00:21:15.830 --> 00:21:18.830
or if it comes, it
will come too late.

00:21:18.830 --> 00:21:21.980
During that period, every single
day, I would sing to Mallory,

00:21:21.980 --> 00:21:24.920
"Somewhere over the
rainbow, there are lungs."

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:28.900
Just the first
line, over and over.

00:21:28.900 --> 00:21:33.130
But then in March, we got the
call on a Friday afternoon,

00:21:33.130 --> 00:21:35.680
and we raced to
get to the hospital

00:21:35.680 --> 00:21:38.470
and hunkered down
for a 24-hour wait.

00:21:38.470 --> 00:21:40.900
During that time, she
actually made it into preop,

00:21:40.900 --> 00:21:43.840
had a lot of tests done, and
we were cautiously optimistic

00:21:43.840 --> 00:21:45.850
that it was going to work.

00:21:45.850 --> 00:21:47.370
But the next
morning, they came in

00:21:47.370 --> 00:21:49.290
to tell us that, while
the lungs were viable,

00:21:49.290 --> 00:21:51.690
they had actually gone
to another candidate.

00:21:51.690 --> 00:21:54.180
We didn't know that Mallory
was a backup candidate,

00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:55.680
and at the time,
we didn't even know

00:21:55.680 --> 00:21:58.080
that that was actually
a thing, which

00:21:58.080 --> 00:21:59.970
leads to insight number five.

00:21:59.970 --> 00:22:03.300
Doctors should err in favor of
giving more information rather

00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:08.630
than less, as it helps patients
manage their expectations.

00:22:08.630 --> 00:22:10.820
In a crazy twist of
fate, the second call

00:22:10.820 --> 00:22:12.650
came 48 hours later.

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:14.510
And again we rushed
to the hospital,

00:22:14.510 --> 00:22:18.440
waited about another 24 hours,
but again, it was a no go.

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:20.600
This time there was
no backup candidate,

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:22.910
but the lungs weren't viable.

00:22:22.910 --> 00:22:24.710
This was the second
dry run, and there

00:22:24.710 --> 00:22:28.250
was to be a third,
which came months later

00:22:28.250 --> 00:22:31.340
after Mallory agreed to
accept high risk lungs.

00:22:31.340 --> 00:22:36.530
High risk lungs are labeled that
when a person has identified

00:22:36.530 --> 00:22:39.770
with one of three behaviors-- a
homosexual, an intravenous drug

00:22:39.770 --> 00:22:43.297
user, or someone who has
spent time in prison.

00:22:43.297 --> 00:22:45.380
The interesting thing about
the high risk category

00:22:45.380 --> 00:22:48.140
is that somebody could be
any one of those things

00:22:48.140 --> 00:22:51.350
and not disclose, so you kind
of wonder, should you accept

00:22:51.350 --> 00:22:52.520
or should you not?

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:55.820
We asked the surgeon and his
answer was actually perfect.

00:22:55.820 --> 00:23:00.080
Dr. [INAUDIBLE] said, I would
not put any lungs in you

00:23:00.080 --> 00:23:01.730
that I didn't feel comfortable.

00:23:01.730 --> 00:23:05.850
Your survival is as important
to me as it is to you.

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:09.000
The fourth call was the
one that ended up working.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.460
On September 11 of 2017--

00:23:11.460 --> 00:23:13.920
sort of an inauspicious
date for transplant--

00:23:13.920 --> 00:23:17.210
Mallory finally made it into
the OR, and after nine hours,

00:23:17.210 --> 00:23:19.290
Dr. [INAUDIBLE]
came out and told us

00:23:19.290 --> 00:23:21.060
he was thrilled
with the outcome.

00:23:21.060 --> 00:23:23.255
She had done quite well.

00:23:23.255 --> 00:23:24.630
But of course
during this period,

00:23:24.630 --> 00:23:26.900
she had vocal paralysis,
unbearable pain,

00:23:26.900 --> 00:23:28.980
a swallowing disorder,
a list of medications

00:23:28.980 --> 00:23:30.647
that would make your
head spin, and this

00:23:30.647 --> 00:23:32.820
is when we experienced that
second round of the pain

00:23:32.820 --> 00:23:34.410
management problem.

00:23:34.410 --> 00:23:37.500
But yet, despite all of
that, to see your daughter

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:39.780
take her first
breath with new lungs

00:23:39.780 --> 00:23:44.900
and no supplemental oxygen is
a sight that's indescribable.

00:23:44.900 --> 00:23:47.360
The rehab for her was
grueling, but a month later,

00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:51.410
on October 12th of
2017, Mallory was home

00:23:51.410 --> 00:23:52.820
celebrating her birthday.

00:23:52.820 --> 00:23:54.590
Well, actually her
home in Pittsburgh,

00:23:54.590 --> 00:23:56.540
because we were still there.

00:23:56.540 --> 00:23:59.150
During those days,
I would sing to her,

00:23:59.150 --> 00:24:01.760
"Somewhere over the
rainbow, there were lungs,"

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:04.010
and you'll note the
rainbow on her cake.

00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:06.440
It was the very
happiest time as we

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:08.990
dared to dream about
a new life, one

00:24:08.990 --> 00:24:12.530
that Mallory would spend back
in California, living with Jack,

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:15.830
surfing, and doing
additional writing.

00:24:15.830 --> 00:24:18.320
But a very short
few weeks later,

00:24:18.320 --> 00:24:20.270
Mallory was readmitted
with pneumonia,

00:24:20.270 --> 00:24:22.220
and almost immediately,
the doctors

00:24:22.220 --> 00:24:25.630
started preparing
me for the worst.

00:24:25.630 --> 00:24:27.130
Now I'm going to
switch and tell you

00:24:27.130 --> 00:24:30.130
a little bit about
Mallory's journals, which

00:24:30.130 --> 00:24:33.290
end up in "Salt in my
Soul, an Unfinished Life."

00:24:33.290 --> 00:24:35.660
Mallory started writing
when she was 15.

00:24:35.660 --> 00:24:38.320
She wrote anywhere she was.

00:24:38.320 --> 00:24:40.278
She wrote at tournament's--
sports tournaments.

00:24:40.278 --> 00:24:41.778
She wrote in the
middle of the night

00:24:41.778 --> 00:24:44.450
when she had insomnia, on
trips, at friends' houses,

00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:47.320
when she was doing
treatment in Hawaii.

00:24:47.320 --> 00:24:50.850
Writing, for her, was
extremely cathartic.

00:24:50.850 --> 00:24:55.100
Now during these years, Mallory
and I were joined at the hip.

00:24:55.100 --> 00:24:56.780
She confided in me
about everything,

00:24:56.780 --> 00:25:00.610
and I felt lucky to have
those years with her.

00:25:00.610 --> 00:25:04.248
What I did to help
her also helped me.

00:25:04.248 --> 00:25:06.040
I cooked for her,
cleaned her [INAUDIBLE],,

00:25:06.040 --> 00:25:07.873
picked up her meds,
anything that would give

00:25:07.873 --> 00:25:09.290
her more time with her friends.

00:25:09.290 --> 00:25:10.990
But in the process,
it gave me a window

00:25:10.990 --> 00:25:12.820
into what her life
was like, something

00:25:12.820 --> 00:25:15.490
most parents of
teenagers don't get.

00:25:15.490 --> 00:25:18.372
Her friends were so used to
me being in the background

00:25:18.372 --> 00:25:20.080
that they treated me
like I was furniture

00:25:20.080 --> 00:25:22.510
and I really learned a
lot about my daughter.

00:25:22.510 --> 00:25:24.940
I wouldn't trade
that for anything.

00:25:24.940 --> 00:25:27.910
But one day, after a very
typical mother-daughter fight,

00:25:27.910 --> 00:25:30.790
Mallory stormed off into
her room, slammed the door,

00:25:30.790 --> 00:25:33.190
and started pounding
on her laptop.

00:25:33.190 --> 00:25:36.190
From then on, I assumed her
journal was a repository

00:25:36.190 --> 00:25:38.410
for all of her anger at me.

00:25:38.410 --> 00:25:41.110
I imagined her detailing
every single thing I had ever

00:25:41.110 --> 00:25:45.070
done wrong as a mother, and
it was a terrifying thought.

00:25:45.070 --> 00:25:48.040
I didn't actually read her
journal until she passed away.

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:49.720
She had kept it
password protected,

00:25:49.720 --> 00:25:52.180
and despite my repeated
attempts to break into it,

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:54.320
was never able to find it.

00:25:54.320 --> 00:25:58.270
But the day of her memorial, I
opened it for the first time,

00:25:58.270 --> 00:25:59.890
hoping to find
something that I could

00:25:59.890 --> 00:26:02.510
use when speaking about her.

00:26:02.510 --> 00:26:06.170
What I found was 2,500 pages,
organized chronologically,

00:26:06.170 --> 00:26:09.800
with each entry date stamped,
in electronic journals,

00:26:09.800 --> 00:26:12.990
with zero expression
of anger at me.

00:26:12.990 --> 00:26:15.350
It was the most precious
and unexpected gift

00:26:15.350 --> 00:26:18.350
a grieving mother
could expect, and I

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:20.870
believe that she left
it that way because she

00:26:20.870 --> 00:26:23.540
knew that I would read it.

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:27.170
Mallory was incredibly
articulate and astute,

00:26:27.170 --> 00:26:29.960
and in her journal she
describes so many things

00:26:29.960 --> 00:26:32.090
that are helpful both to
the medical community,

00:26:32.090 --> 00:26:35.360
to other patients, to
health care providers,

00:26:35.360 --> 00:26:38.000
and to those who love
people with chronic illness.

00:26:38.000 --> 00:26:41.000
She highlights big picture
issues that are important,

00:26:41.000 --> 00:26:44.300
but she also talks about
how the daily decisions

00:26:44.300 --> 00:26:49.460
that each caretaker makes
can impact the day to day

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:51.830
quality of life for a patient.

00:26:51.830 --> 00:26:55.220
That includes doctors, nurses,
respiratory therapists, OT,

00:26:55.220 --> 00:26:58.790
case managers, janitors--
the list goes on and on.

00:26:58.790 --> 00:27:00.800
Which leads to my
final insight that I

00:27:00.800 --> 00:27:02.720
will share of hers today.

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:04.670
A life-threatening
illness puts you

00:27:04.670 --> 00:27:07.850
at the intersection of so
many public health issues,

00:27:07.850 --> 00:27:10.160
and turns you into
an accidental expert

00:27:10.160 --> 00:27:15.700
about what can and should
be improved in patient care.

00:27:15.700 --> 00:27:19.090
I still struggle every day to
accept that Mallory is gone.

00:27:19.090 --> 00:27:21.760
When she first passed
away, I spent months

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:23.770
reading and rereading
her journals,

00:27:23.770 --> 00:27:27.220
laughing and crying
at every page.

00:27:27.220 --> 00:27:32.730
The big surprise was that her
journals revealed a darker

00:27:32.730 --> 00:27:34.860
truth about her
experiences and emotions

00:27:34.860 --> 00:27:38.220
that she had not wanted
to share during her life.

00:27:38.220 --> 00:27:41.710
Her facade of perfection
was just that.

00:27:41.710 --> 00:27:43.880
Malory did live happy.

00:27:43.880 --> 00:27:46.120
But in her writing
she does express anger

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:49.690
at her disease, shame about
her body and its failings,

00:27:49.690 --> 00:27:53.140
the difficulty of straddling
the sick and the well world,

00:27:53.140 --> 00:27:54.770
her fear of dying.

00:27:54.770 --> 00:27:56.830
But along with that,
the importance to her

00:27:56.830 --> 00:28:00.460
of friendship, her
deep desire for love,

00:28:00.460 --> 00:28:02.980
and most heartbreaking
to me, the fact that she

00:28:02.980 --> 00:28:05.380
wanted a child.

00:28:05.380 --> 00:28:08.020
It's impossible to capture
Mallory's life in one talk

00:28:08.020 --> 00:28:10.660
or share all of the
insights that she offers.

00:28:10.660 --> 00:28:12.700
She was awe-inspiring,
and her memory

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:15.700
will be forever etched in
the hearts and minds of those

00:28:15.700 --> 00:28:19.210
who loved her, but will now be
also in the hearts and minds

00:28:19.210 --> 00:28:22.080
of those who read her work.

00:28:22.080 --> 00:28:24.800
Losing Mallory was catastrophic.

00:28:24.800 --> 00:28:27.240
There's no other
way to describe it.

00:28:27.240 --> 00:28:29.120
But what we've
come to understand

00:28:29.120 --> 00:28:31.460
is that sometimes, a
heartbreaking ending can

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:33.890
be the beginning of a triumph.

00:28:33.890 --> 00:28:37.730
Mallory's legacy is in her
wit, her words, and her wisdom,

00:28:37.730 --> 00:28:39.000
the salt in her soul.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:39.500
Thank you.

00:28:46.520 --> 00:28:49.790
So I think now we're going to
invite Jack, the boyfriend, who

00:28:49.790 --> 00:28:53.030
actually writes in the book, and
Mark, the dad and husband, who

00:28:53.030 --> 00:28:55.220
also contributes in
the book, to come up.

00:28:55.220 --> 00:28:56.940
And if anybody
has any questions,

00:28:56.940 --> 00:28:58.548
we'd be happy to answer them.

00:28:58.548 --> 00:29:01.090
AUDIENCE: Mallory comes from a
family with a lot of resources

00:29:01.090 --> 00:29:03.298
and the ability to do some
pretty incredible things--

00:29:03.298 --> 00:29:05.413
moving around the country,
all the time you were

00:29:05.413 --> 00:29:06.580
able to dedicate, et cetera.

00:29:06.580 --> 00:29:08.350
How applicable is
this experience

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:09.850
to other kinds of
families who don't

00:29:09.850 --> 00:29:11.100
have those kinds of resources?

00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:12.892
DIANE SHADER SMITH:
Well, it's interesting.

00:29:12.892 --> 00:29:15.010
One of the palliative
care social workers

00:29:15.010 --> 00:29:17.530
at Children's Hospital,
whose name is Danielle Jonas,

00:29:17.530 --> 00:29:19.270
told me very early on.

00:29:19.270 --> 00:29:21.610
She had come to the hospital
and spent time with Mallory

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:23.050
and she knew about the writing.

00:29:23.050 --> 00:29:25.180
And she said to
me, you absolutely

00:29:25.180 --> 00:29:28.420
must make the story
public because I

00:29:28.420 --> 00:29:31.990
work with under-served families
at Children's Hospital in LA,

00:29:31.990 --> 00:29:33.910
and when their child
dies, they actually

00:29:33.910 --> 00:29:36.490
think that their child
died because they

00:29:36.490 --> 00:29:39.080
couldn't provide better
care or better resources.

00:29:39.080 --> 00:29:41.080
And the message here is
that you can have money.

00:29:41.080 --> 00:29:41.913
You can have access.

00:29:41.913 --> 00:29:42.940
You can have privilege.

00:29:42.940 --> 00:29:45.880
You can still suffer and
your child can still die.

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:47.350
Mallory suffered.

00:29:47.350 --> 00:29:50.200
Having access to health care
and the transplant, of course,

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:52.070
extended her life a little bit.

00:29:52.070 --> 00:29:54.410
But at the end of the day,
it didn't change the outcome.

00:29:54.410 --> 00:29:57.100
And so hopefully people
will learn from the message,

00:29:57.100 --> 00:29:58.030
don't feel guilty.

00:29:58.030 --> 00:29:58.750
Don't feel bad.

00:29:58.750 --> 00:30:00.040
Do what you can.

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:01.900
But disease runs its
own course sometimes

00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:04.737
and there's nothing you can do.

00:30:04.737 --> 00:30:06.570
AUDIENCE: Thank you so
much for your courage

00:30:06.570 --> 00:30:08.040
to share this
story, and I'm just

00:30:08.040 --> 00:30:09.930
amazed how you, as
a mother, held it

00:30:09.930 --> 00:30:11.142
all together in sharing this.

00:30:11.142 --> 00:30:13.350
DIANE SHADER SMITH: I have
to fight crying each time.

00:30:13.350 --> 00:30:14.225
AUDIENCE: Oh my gosh.

00:30:14.225 --> 00:30:19.380
You're amazingly articulate
and your words were beautiful.

00:30:19.380 --> 00:30:21.510
I wanted to find
out how you've been

00:30:21.510 --> 00:30:24.750
able to translate all of
this incredible knowledge

00:30:24.750 --> 00:30:28.770
and perspective to
the medical community.

00:30:28.770 --> 00:30:31.830
I can imagine you feel
it's your life's desire

00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:34.830
to see change in the system
to better help people

00:30:34.830 --> 00:30:36.870
of the future who
will have to be

00:30:36.870 --> 00:30:39.280
under these horrible
circumstances.

00:30:39.280 --> 00:30:40.950
What's happening in
that path for you,

00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:43.590
and have you found any
headway or response

00:30:43.590 --> 00:30:46.143
to this amazing work and
the work that you're doing?

00:30:46.143 --> 00:30:48.810
DIANE SHADER SMITH: So it hasn't
even been three weeks, I think,

00:30:48.810 --> 00:30:50.310
that the book came
out on March 12.

00:30:50.310 --> 00:30:52.890
So I'm sort of at the
beginning of the journey.

00:30:52.890 --> 00:30:56.880
I am doing 70 talks, and
more offers are coming in.

00:30:56.880 --> 00:31:01.465
And so far, I've spoken to
one medical school and a group

00:31:01.465 --> 00:31:03.840
of residents-- a resident's
council on the medical school

00:31:03.840 --> 00:31:05.920
at University of Pennsylvania.

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:08.250
And what I'm hearing
is that the message

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:10.410
is very important
for them because they

00:31:10.410 --> 00:31:13.512
will learn from an
actual case study,

00:31:13.512 --> 00:31:15.720
in addition to what they're
studying in the textbook.

00:31:15.720 --> 00:31:18.660
But I've had offers
from some other

00:31:18.660 --> 00:31:20.400
of the medical
professionals that I'm

00:31:20.400 --> 00:31:24.023
speaking at their institutions
to do some more extensive work,

00:31:24.023 --> 00:31:25.440
and it was suggested,
for example,

00:31:25.440 --> 00:31:26.950
that I work on curriculum.

00:31:26.950 --> 00:31:29.850
And I will do that, because
now that Mallory is not

00:31:29.850 --> 00:31:33.240
here, all of the energy
and passion and commitment

00:31:33.240 --> 00:31:35.190
that I had to
taking care of her,

00:31:35.190 --> 00:31:38.190
I want to translate that
into taking her messages on.

00:31:38.190 --> 00:31:40.620
People who've read the
book write to me every day.

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:43.312
It's unbelievable that
it's helping empower them.

00:31:43.312 --> 00:31:44.520
It's helping them understand.

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:47.320
And fortunately, the
press has been amazing,

00:31:47.320 --> 00:31:49.380
so I don't have to
be as braggy as I

00:31:49.380 --> 00:31:50.680
might have to be otherwise.

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:53.340
But it is important, first,
to get the word out there,

00:31:53.340 --> 00:31:55.230
and then to take it
to the next level,

00:31:55.230 --> 00:31:57.810
to try to figure out
which particular area I

00:31:57.810 --> 00:31:59.100
think I'll spend most time on.

00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:04.770
I know for me, I think that the
surprising thing is that, when

00:32:04.770 --> 00:32:07.915
I first worked on the
journal and thought

00:32:07.915 --> 00:32:09.540
I was going to bring
it to publication,

00:32:09.540 --> 00:32:10.695
that it was going
to be most relevant

00:32:10.695 --> 00:32:13.020
and important for the CF
community and the transplant

00:32:13.020 --> 00:32:13.530
community.

00:32:13.530 --> 00:32:15.450
But what I've sort of
come to understand is,

00:32:15.450 --> 00:32:18.630
people like it in that community
because it sort of gives them

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:21.430
that feeling of familiarity
and shared experience.

00:32:21.430 --> 00:32:23.430
But there are a lot
of other communities

00:32:23.430 --> 00:32:26.070
that I hadn't thought would
be benefited by, for example,

00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:27.630
the mental illness community.

00:32:27.630 --> 00:32:29.610
I've done a talk for
the National Alliance

00:32:29.610 --> 00:32:31.650
on Mental Illness
in Los Angeles,

00:32:31.650 --> 00:32:34.307
and they explained that all
of the issues about fear,

00:32:34.307 --> 00:32:36.390
depression, and anxiety
that Mallory writes about,

00:32:36.390 --> 00:32:38.970
and the issue of disclosure
and invisible illness

00:32:38.970 --> 00:32:40.270
are so important.

00:32:40.270 --> 00:32:43.200
And so I recognize I'm
at sort of the beginning

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:44.817
of this journey,
and I would love

00:32:44.817 --> 00:32:46.650
you to ask me the
question in the year, when

00:32:46.650 --> 00:32:48.690
I finish most of
the talks, and then

00:32:48.690 --> 00:32:50.090
I will be sure to report back.

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:51.690
But I will definitely
do something.

00:32:51.690 --> 00:32:53.450
I can't imagine
anything more important.

00:32:53.450 --> 00:32:55.200
AUDIENCE: What are
some of the things that

00:32:55.200 --> 00:32:58.780
are happening today to help
with this type of outcome?

00:32:58.780 --> 00:33:01.740
What are some of the things that
you're looking at research-wise

00:33:01.740 --> 00:33:04.740
to help patients such as this?

00:33:04.740 --> 00:33:10.280
MARK SMITH: Well, some
friends of Mallory

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:13.050
who collaborated with her
to organize a charity called

00:33:13.050 --> 00:33:14.790
Lunges with Lungs--

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:18.270
and there's a link to
that on the website--

00:33:18.270 --> 00:33:21.630
it raises money for
rejection research, which

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:26.100
is a big problem, obviously,
in transplant cases, not just

00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:29.140
lung transplants but
across the board.

00:33:29.140 --> 00:33:34.200
And then we're also
working to promote

00:33:34.200 --> 00:33:36.420
an experimental treatment
that Mallory got.

00:33:36.420 --> 00:33:39.990
This story is in the book and
in the postscript, especially.

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:44.672
It's called phage therapy and
it was kind of a Hail Mary pass

00:33:44.672 --> 00:33:46.380
that we made at the
end of Mallory's life

00:33:46.380 --> 00:33:50.370
to see if we could eradicate
the B. cepacia infection

00:33:50.370 --> 00:33:52.140
and save her life.

00:33:52.140 --> 00:33:54.780
We did end up getting
phage therapy for Mallory,

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:58.800
but it was about
a week too late.

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:02.340
And she had a few doses.

00:34:02.340 --> 00:34:05.730
The autopsy indicated that
the medicine was working,

00:34:05.730 --> 00:34:08.670
but it was too late
to save her life.

00:34:08.670 --> 00:34:11.310
Since she died, interest
in phage therapy

00:34:11.310 --> 00:34:17.100
has been reignited, and
a cystic fibrosis patient

00:34:17.100 --> 00:34:21.000
in San Diego with a
nasty pulmonary infection

00:34:21.000 --> 00:34:24.915
was rejected for
transplant, and then

00:34:24.915 --> 00:34:26.790
treated with phage
therapy, and then put back

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:29.444
on the transplant list.

00:34:29.444 --> 00:34:32.460
And there's other cases
at Yale and in the UK

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:36.270
and one more in Pittsburgh
where they have successfully

00:34:36.270 --> 00:34:39.929
used the therapy that we
tried to get for Mallory

00:34:39.929 --> 00:34:42.989
and cleared an infection in
a cystic fibrosis patient,

00:34:42.989 --> 00:34:46.290
and we're hopeful that that
will become a standard part

00:34:46.290 --> 00:34:47.195
of the treatment.

00:34:47.195 --> 00:34:48.570
DIANE SHADER SMITH:
And we should

00:34:48.570 --> 00:34:50.790
mention that we're donating
all profits from the book.

00:34:50.790 --> 00:34:52.710
We don't want to make
any money from the book.

00:34:52.710 --> 00:34:55.060
Both Mark and I are full
time working professionals

00:34:55.060 --> 00:34:57.120
and we don't need the
money, and so we're

00:34:57.120 --> 00:35:00.510
using this tour to raise
money and awareness

00:35:00.510 --> 00:35:04.950
for phage therapy
because by the year 2050,

00:35:04.950 --> 00:35:07.350
10 million people per year
will die from superbugs,

00:35:07.350 --> 00:35:10.110
and phage therapy will be
relevant and applicable,

00:35:10.110 --> 00:35:12.960
not just for patients with CF
or those immunocompromised,

00:35:12.960 --> 00:35:14.980
but everybody who gets
a superbug infection.

00:35:14.980 --> 00:35:17.010
And if you don't know
about phage therapy,

00:35:17.010 --> 00:35:18.630
you can read about
the journey that we

00:35:18.630 --> 00:35:20.120
had with it in the book.

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:21.370
You can also Google it online.

00:35:21.370 --> 00:35:23.670
It's [INAUDIBLE] use the Google.

00:35:23.670 --> 00:35:26.300
You can Google it and you'll
find a lot of information

00:35:26.300 --> 00:35:26.800
about it.

00:35:26.800 --> 00:35:27.650
It's very important.

00:35:27.650 --> 00:35:29.400
That was not an intended
plug, by the way.

00:35:29.400 --> 00:35:30.970
I just--

00:35:30.970 --> 00:35:34.380
MARK SMITH: There's also a
link on the web page, which

00:35:34.380 --> 00:35:38.760
is SaltInMySoulBook.com, a
link to donate to phage therapy

00:35:38.760 --> 00:35:40.380
or to the rejection research.

