JACK: So she loved her friends.

00:36:41.370 --> 00:36:42.620
She loved the environment.

00:36:42.620 --> 00:36:44.610
She loved the ocean,
which had a lot of salt

00:36:44.610 --> 00:36:47.000
and it helped her breathe more.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:36:49.520
She knew that she
would plant seeds

00:36:49.520 --> 00:36:53.240
that would grow into trees that
would create shade that she

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:54.830
would never be able to sit in.

00:36:54.830 --> 00:36:57.800
So that was very clear for her.

00:36:57.800 --> 00:37:00.690
Your question is how
did it affect us.

00:37:00.690 --> 00:37:04.430
I thought that some of the
more challenging moments--

00:37:04.430 --> 00:37:06.290
seeing her through
transplant, seeing

00:37:06.290 --> 00:37:09.290
her go to the brink of
death and come back,

00:37:09.290 --> 00:37:12.590
holding her in our hands when
she passed away together--

00:37:12.590 --> 00:37:14.990
I thought those would
be the harder moments.

00:37:14.990 --> 00:37:16.970
But the harder moments
have actually been now.

00:37:16.970 --> 00:37:20.530
How do you honor a legacy
that is so extraordinary?

00:37:20.530 --> 00:37:22.280
That's the question I
ask myself routinely

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:25.310
and it's one that we all
have different answers to,

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:27.500
but it's one we're
still figuring out.

00:37:27.500 --> 00:37:33.830
She wanted a future that her
desired child, the kid she

00:37:33.830 --> 00:37:36.650
hoped for, would be
able to be happy in,

00:37:36.650 --> 00:37:41.423
so she was very cognizant of
the world that she left behind.

00:37:41.423 --> 00:37:43.090
DIANE SHADER SMITH:
I would answer that,

00:37:43.090 --> 00:37:48.080
and I would say very simply,
Mallory chose to live happy,

00:37:48.080 --> 00:37:51.080
and Mark and I, from the
time she was very young,

00:37:51.080 --> 00:37:54.080
made the decision that we were
not going to live a pity party,

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:57.110
and that, however short her time
was, it would be a lot of fun.

00:37:57.110 --> 00:38:00.920
And we had a magnificent and
amazing 25 years with her.

00:38:00.920 --> 00:38:02.900
I would not trade
it for anything.

00:38:02.900 --> 00:38:05.510
And I do believe that
Mallory accomplished

00:38:05.510 --> 00:38:09.350
and did as much in 25 years as
many people do in a lifetime.

00:38:09.350 --> 00:38:10.520
It just was condensed.

00:38:10.520 --> 00:38:12.860
And now the loss for
us is catastrophic,

00:38:12.860 --> 00:38:17.270
but when you read the
material that she left,

00:38:17.270 --> 00:38:19.860
you won't believe it.

00:38:19.860 --> 00:38:22.400
It's just staggering how
she's able to articulate.

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:25.880
She dealt with the highest
highs and the lowest lows,

00:38:25.880 --> 00:38:30.470
and her resilience, her
strength, her determination,

00:38:30.470 --> 00:38:31.820
her desire to live--

00:38:31.820 --> 00:38:33.900
she left instructions
before transplant.

00:38:33.900 --> 00:38:36.650
She wanted ECMO, she
wanted ventilator,

00:38:36.650 --> 00:38:39.260
she wanted any heroics
necessary to stay alive.

00:38:39.260 --> 00:38:40.673
She wanted to
live, and it's hard

00:38:40.673 --> 00:38:43.340
not to be happy when you're with
somebody who, despite the worst

00:38:43.340 --> 00:38:46.040
and most overwhelming
obstacles, gets up

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:48.590
every day with a smile on
her face and pushes forward.

00:38:48.590 --> 00:38:51.404
That sets the tone.

00:38:51.404 --> 00:38:54.170
JACK: I have a phrase
that encapsulates that.

00:38:54.170 --> 00:38:55.790
Mallory had a knack
that she was very

00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:58.040
good at of turning some
of her darkest moments

00:38:58.040 --> 00:38:59.960
into some of her finest hours.

00:38:59.960 --> 00:39:02.575
She was a champion all the
time and had so much resolve

00:39:02.575 --> 00:39:06.420
that I'm still inspired by.

00:39:06.420 --> 00:39:09.020
MARK SMITH: Mallory lived
happy, but Diane and I also

00:39:09.020 --> 00:39:11.450
strove to be happy.

00:39:11.450 --> 00:39:14.960
My feeling was, if
we allowed ourselves

00:39:14.960 --> 00:39:17.930
to become despondent
because of her illness,

00:39:17.930 --> 00:39:22.070
then the message she would get
is, she had ruined our lives.

00:39:22.070 --> 00:39:24.920
And the truth is she
did not ruin our lives.

00:39:24.920 --> 00:39:27.330
She enriched them greatly.

00:39:27.330 --> 00:39:30.770
And we always tried to
find the joy in every day

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:37.160
and to squeeze every
last drop of life out.

00:39:37.160 --> 00:39:40.160
And I'm confident that we did.

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:43.250
I would not say that
Mallory had an unhappy life.

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:48.690
I think that, overall, she
had a blessed and happy life.

00:39:48.690 --> 00:39:50.690
AUDIENCE: Thank you guys
all for coming so much.

00:39:50.690 --> 00:39:51.960
I really appreciate it.

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:56.060
Diane, I just wanted to
compliment you and comment

00:39:56.060 --> 00:39:59.415
on your vigorous attitude with
this whole entire process.

00:39:59.415 --> 00:40:01.290
We know it's not an easy
thing to go through.

00:40:01.290 --> 00:40:03.832
I was raised by a single mother
myself and she was definitely

00:40:03.832 --> 00:40:06.260
momma bear my whole
life, still is, in fact.

00:40:06.260 --> 00:40:08.060
So to you two, I
wanted to know, how

00:40:08.060 --> 00:40:10.820
can we, as men and
boyfriends, support

00:40:10.820 --> 00:40:11.820
throughout this journey?

00:40:11.820 --> 00:40:13.442
How can we offer our support?

00:40:13.442 --> 00:40:14.900
DIANE SHADER SMITH:
Make your joke.

00:40:14.900 --> 00:40:15.660
Tell your joke.

00:40:15.660 --> 00:40:16.400
MARK SMITH: What's my joke?

00:40:16.400 --> 00:40:17.692
DIANE SHADER SMITH: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:17.692 --> 00:40:20.300
MARK SMITH: Oh yeah.

00:40:20.300 --> 00:40:28.347
When Diane started setting up
all the talks on her book tour

00:40:28.347 --> 00:40:29.930
and she started
working on her speech,

00:40:29.930 --> 00:40:32.000
and I helped her with
the speech and it

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:35.000
went through multiple drafts.

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:41.000
She asked if I wanted to speak
too, and at a couple of events

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:44.540
I've spoken about phage
therapy, but the audience

00:40:44.540 --> 00:40:47.330
that she has for the book talks
isn't really the right audience

00:40:47.330 --> 00:40:50.750
for the phage therapy talk.

00:40:50.750 --> 00:40:53.450
But Diane did say that she
wanted me to come and travel

00:40:53.450 --> 00:41:00.863
with her and attend as many
of the speeches as I could.

00:41:00.863 --> 00:41:02.280
And so I told her
that I was going

00:41:02.280 --> 00:41:05.300
to get myself one of
those little red vests

00:41:05.300 --> 00:41:08.770
that says "Emotional
support animal."

00:41:08.770 --> 00:41:10.520
DIANE SHADER SMITH: I
keep waiting for him

00:41:10.520 --> 00:41:11.330
to show up in it one day.

00:41:11.330 --> 00:41:13.705
MARK SMITH: Yeah, I haven't
figured out how to do it yet.

00:41:13.705 --> 00:41:16.550
The dog kind don't
really fit a human body,

00:41:16.550 --> 00:41:19.720
so I may have to
commission it to be made.

00:41:22.460 --> 00:41:27.410
But in response to your
question, how can you help,

00:41:27.410 --> 00:41:29.930
one of the things that
is really poignant when

00:41:29.930 --> 00:41:32.870
you read Mallory's book,
especially if you knew her

00:41:32.870 --> 00:41:36.680
and then you read the book,
is how much suffering she

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:37.820
went through.

00:41:37.820 --> 00:41:40.910
And she chose not to
share a lot of it with me.

00:41:40.910 --> 00:41:43.100
I think she shared
more with her mother.

00:41:43.100 --> 00:41:45.830
Some of her friends say
they actually felt guilty

00:41:45.830 --> 00:41:49.910
when they read the book for not
knowing how much suffering she

00:41:49.910 --> 00:41:51.650
went through.

00:41:51.650 --> 00:41:55.710
But she concealed that from
us because she loved us.

00:41:55.710 --> 00:41:58.880
And I think it's important
for everybody, men and women,

00:41:58.880 --> 00:42:02.990
to understand that you see
only a very tiny little bit

00:42:02.990 --> 00:42:06.350
of what's going on in
another person's life,

00:42:06.350 --> 00:42:09.300
and there's often
a whole iceberg

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:10.920
there below the surface.

00:42:10.920 --> 00:42:14.190
So keep that in mind, I think,
when you deal with people,

00:42:14.190 --> 00:42:15.370
whether they're sick or not.

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:17.418
Sometimes you don't
know that they're sick.

00:42:17.418 --> 00:42:19.710
DIANE SHADER SMITH: I want
to answer that question too.

00:42:19.710 --> 00:42:23.720
So I would say two words--

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:24.620
show up.

00:42:24.620 --> 00:42:28.040
And I can give an example
and an anecdote with Jack.

00:42:28.040 --> 00:42:32.900
So there was really catastrophic
news in the summer of August--

00:42:32.900 --> 00:42:35.330
I think it was August of 2016--

00:42:35.330 --> 00:42:39.282
when Stanford came in
and said, the antibiotics

00:42:39.282 --> 00:42:41.240
aren't working anymore
and we're out of options

00:42:41.240 --> 00:42:43.850
and I don't know that any
center is going to accept you.

00:42:43.850 --> 00:42:45.590
And so we said--

00:42:45.590 --> 00:42:47.540
I said-- no pity party.

00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:48.500
No negativity.

00:42:48.500 --> 00:42:50.450
Nothing in the room that's bad.

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:53.340
And Jack, who had been
ever-present, always there, day

00:42:53.340 --> 00:42:55.340
in and day out, just
disappeared for three days,

00:42:55.340 --> 00:42:57.770
and Mallory was devastated.

00:42:57.770 --> 00:42:59.510
And then he finally
came and explained--

00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:01.468
and you can ask him if
you want what happened--

00:43:01.468 --> 00:43:03.267
but what he
explained to me was--

00:43:03.267 --> 00:43:04.850
or he explained to
Mallory and Mallory

00:43:04.850 --> 00:43:07.940
told me-- was that he heard
me with my no negativity

00:43:07.940 --> 00:43:10.310
and he was too sad and
crying and couldn't be there.

00:43:10.310 --> 00:43:13.190
And Mallory said very clearly,
I don't care if you cry.

00:43:13.190 --> 00:43:15.560
I don't care if you're sad.

00:43:15.560 --> 00:43:17.270
But I want you in
the room with me.

00:43:17.270 --> 00:43:19.100
And I think that the most
important thing-- it's sort of

00:43:19.100 --> 00:43:19.730
like with Mark.

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:21.647
If he doesn't speak, if
he doesn't do anything

00:43:21.647 --> 00:43:24.855
more than just show up,
it's an amazing support

00:43:24.855 --> 00:43:26.480
to know that somebody
is there, to have

00:43:26.480 --> 00:43:29.220
a rock when you're alone and
struggling with whatever it is.

00:43:29.220 --> 00:43:29.960
MARK SMITH: I
don't just show up.

00:43:29.960 --> 00:43:31.002
I also lead the applause.

00:43:34.755 --> 00:43:36.630
AUDIENCE: So Jack, I'll
shift it over to you.

00:43:36.630 --> 00:43:37.550
JACK: Sure.

00:43:37.550 --> 00:43:37.820
Yeah, obviously--

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:38.760
DIANE SHADER SMITH: Do
you remember that episode?

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:39.343
Remember that?

00:43:39.343 --> 00:43:40.580
JACK: Of course, yeah.

00:43:40.580 --> 00:43:42.500
There's this perception
now that I'd always

00:43:42.500 --> 00:43:45.060
been a good partner,
a good boyfriend.

00:43:45.060 --> 00:43:47.180
But it obviously
wasn't always the case.

00:43:47.180 --> 00:43:50.370
Mallory was a great
teacher as well as partner,

00:43:50.370 --> 00:43:55.340
so I learned a lot from dating
her that I hope to share now.

00:43:55.340 --> 00:43:56.840
One of the struggles
that I face now

00:43:56.840 --> 00:44:01.400
is, there is no word for
what position I hold now.

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:02.930
I'm not a widow.

00:44:02.930 --> 00:44:06.140
Mallory and I talked about
marriage and children,

00:44:06.140 --> 00:44:08.618
but decided to put off
engagement and things like that

00:44:08.618 --> 00:44:10.160
so that she could
fight for her life.

00:44:10.160 --> 00:44:12.380
That's a pretty important goal.

00:44:12.380 --> 00:44:15.110
But now I think of
myself as a quasi-widow,

00:44:15.110 --> 00:44:17.750
the former boyfriend to
this incredible woman.

00:44:17.750 --> 00:44:19.850
And so to answer
your question, how

00:44:19.850 --> 00:44:24.260
do we as men, or former
boyfriends in my case,

00:44:24.260 --> 00:44:27.720
honor her legacy and show
that in their restraint?

00:44:27.720 --> 00:44:29.180
And it's one I'm
still working on.

00:44:29.180 --> 00:44:30.805
One of the most
rewarding parts of this

00:44:30.805 --> 00:44:35.630
has been the inspiration people
have shared with me of Mallory

00:44:35.630 --> 00:44:37.340
and I as a couple.

00:44:37.340 --> 00:44:40.580
It's not like she became sick
after I started dating her.

00:44:40.580 --> 00:44:42.395
I knew all of that
upfront, going into it.

00:44:42.395 --> 00:44:44.180
But she was such an
extraordinary woman

00:44:44.180 --> 00:44:48.750
that it was so clear to
stay with her for me.

00:44:48.750 --> 00:44:50.960
I have no regrets of dating her.

00:44:50.960 --> 00:44:51.868
She was incredible.

00:44:51.868 --> 00:44:52.910
AUDIENCE: Thank you guys.

00:44:55.700 --> 00:44:59.298
AUDIENCE: So Tim and I have
a 22-year-old son with CF.

00:44:59.298 --> 00:45:00.590
DIANE SHADER SMITH: Oh, you do?

00:45:00.590 --> 00:45:01.250
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:45:01.250 --> 00:45:05.780
So thank you, all three of you,
for sharing your experiences.

00:45:05.780 --> 00:45:07.650
And I could ask you
a lot of questions,

00:45:07.650 --> 00:45:13.040
but I really wanted to focus on
your two issues of disclosure

00:45:13.040 --> 00:45:15.600
because there were
two perspectives.

00:45:15.600 --> 00:45:20.510
One was, would you
still advise a patient

00:45:20.510 --> 00:45:24.460
with CF or other chronic
illness, to disclose that to--

00:45:24.460 --> 00:45:26.510
DIANE SHADER SMITH: 100%,
and I can explain why,

00:45:26.510 --> 00:45:28.350
or if you want to ask
your second question.

00:45:28.350 --> 00:45:29.900
AUDIENCE: And the
second question

00:45:29.900 --> 00:45:35.420
is, the lack of disclosure on
the part of the medical team,

00:45:35.420 --> 00:45:38.420
with respect to, you were the
second in line for the lung

00:45:38.420 --> 00:45:39.890
transplant, things like that.

00:45:39.890 --> 00:45:44.530
Are there ways that we can help
them to be more open with us?

00:45:44.530 --> 00:45:47.030
DIANE SHADER SMITH: Well OK,
I'll answer the second question

00:45:47.030 --> 00:45:48.500
first.

00:45:48.500 --> 00:45:51.260
By speaking out, we're
raising awareness.

00:45:51.260 --> 00:45:53.840
And I have already
given 15 talks

00:45:53.840 --> 00:45:56.158
and I've already done a
lot of press interviews

00:45:56.158 --> 00:45:58.200
and I've already heard
back from a lot of people.

00:45:58.200 --> 00:46:01.585
And so it sparks conversation
and it triggers conversation,

00:46:01.585 --> 00:46:03.710
which, back to your question,
what I'm going to do,

00:46:03.710 --> 00:46:05.127
I'm going to poke
the bear is what

00:46:05.127 --> 00:46:06.419
I'm going to do in the process.

00:46:06.419 --> 00:46:08.044
I don't know what
I'm going to land on,

00:46:08.044 --> 00:46:10.010
but for right now I'm
going to raise the issue.

00:46:10.010 --> 00:46:12.385
And it's funny, because a lot
of the medical institutions

00:46:12.385 --> 00:46:13.920
wanted to see the
talk, and I was

00:46:13.920 --> 00:46:15.170
like, I'm not sending my talk.

00:46:15.170 --> 00:46:16.253
You don't have to take me.

00:46:16.253 --> 00:46:18.770
But it took me a
long time to land

00:46:18.770 --> 00:46:22.080
on what I felt was most
important to share.

00:46:22.080 --> 00:46:25.938
But I think if you just
express to your caretakers--

00:46:25.938 --> 00:46:27.980
your CF team, I'm not sure
where you're treated--

00:46:27.980 --> 00:46:29.450
that you want full information.

00:46:29.450 --> 00:46:30.860
And part of Mallory's--

00:46:30.860 --> 00:46:32.990
and I mentioned this
early in the talk.

00:46:32.990 --> 00:46:35.060
Part of why she
got such good care

00:46:35.060 --> 00:46:37.520
is because she was able to
articulate exactly what she

00:46:37.520 --> 00:46:38.903
was feeling and thinking.

00:46:38.903 --> 00:46:40.070
She understood her symptoms.

00:46:40.070 --> 00:46:41.630
She knew what her
treatments were.

00:46:41.630 --> 00:46:43.860
She understood what was
happening in her body.

00:46:43.860 --> 00:46:46.550
And I think that her
being so open and honest

00:46:46.550 --> 00:46:49.927
and communicative helped
them be that way with her.

00:46:49.927 --> 00:46:52.010
But back to your question
about whether disclosure

00:46:52.010 --> 00:46:53.930
is important.

00:46:53.930 --> 00:46:56.930
I overwhelmingly
feel that when you

00:46:56.930 --> 00:46:59.450
tell people what
is going on, 90%

00:46:59.450 --> 00:47:02.000
of the people, 99% of the
people, whatever the number is,

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.100
are supportive and
caring and kind.

00:47:04.100 --> 00:47:07.190
If an employer
withdraws an offer,

00:47:07.190 --> 00:47:10.635
it's good that your son
is not starting that job,

00:47:10.635 --> 00:47:12.260
because you don't
want your son to work

00:47:12.260 --> 00:47:14.135
in a place that doesn't
want somebody to have

00:47:14.135 --> 00:47:15.650
that as a chronic illness.

00:47:15.650 --> 00:47:18.440
And I didn't want
Mallory to take that job.

00:47:18.440 --> 00:47:20.180
She was really sick at the time.

00:47:20.180 --> 00:47:22.067
She had a great
freelance writing career.

00:47:22.067 --> 00:47:23.400
She had plenty of opportunities.

00:47:23.400 --> 00:47:27.090
What she was longing for
was that office feeling.

00:47:27.090 --> 00:47:29.160
She was so jealous
of all of her friends

00:47:29.160 --> 00:47:30.990
who got to go to Uber
or Lyft or Google

00:47:30.990 --> 00:47:33.300
or Facebook or Airbnb
and all the places.

00:47:33.300 --> 00:47:36.000
They were all working in
these cool startups and fun

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:39.360
companies, and she
was at home and felt

00:47:39.360 --> 00:47:40.930
very lonely and very isolated.

00:47:40.930 --> 00:47:43.740
I said to her, you are going
to compromise your health

00:47:43.740 --> 00:47:44.328
by doing it.

00:47:44.328 --> 00:47:45.870
And as it turned
out, she was already

00:47:45.870 --> 00:47:49.350
compromised to the point where,
a week after that incident

00:47:49.350 --> 00:47:51.760
happened, she ended up
back in the hospital.

00:47:51.760 --> 00:47:54.100
And it was very clear to me
she shouldn't take the job.

00:47:54.100 --> 00:47:56.220
But that said, I
raised the anecdote

00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:58.860
because I think it's important
for people to remember,

00:47:58.860 --> 00:48:00.810
and I think that--

00:48:00.810 --> 00:48:02.700
my advice to you
as a mom to mom is

00:48:02.700 --> 00:48:04.800
to help your son
figure out a career

00:48:04.800 --> 00:48:08.220
that he can do with his
limitations that will embrace

00:48:08.220 --> 00:48:10.180
and accept him for who he is.

00:48:10.180 --> 00:48:13.100
And now, with the friggin'
portable vests, I mean--

00:48:13.100 --> 00:48:14.850
Mallory would be a lot
healthier, I think,

00:48:14.850 --> 00:48:17.872
if she had been able to take
that vest everywhere with her

00:48:17.872 --> 00:48:19.830
and not have had to skip
some of the treatments

00:48:19.830 --> 00:48:22.320
for whatever reasons that
she chose to skip them,

00:48:22.320 --> 00:48:24.030
and she was pretty compliant.

00:48:24.030 --> 00:48:29.580
MARK SMITH: On that
issue of the medical team

00:48:29.580 --> 00:48:31.380
disclosing more to
you, I think just

00:48:31.380 --> 00:48:36.750
by talking about the issue, we
encourage medical professionals

00:48:36.750 --> 00:48:39.660
to consider the disclosure
issue from the standpoint

00:48:39.660 --> 00:48:42.910
of the patient and the family.

00:48:42.910 --> 00:48:44.730
And I think they
mostly consider it

00:48:44.730 --> 00:48:49.648
from the standpoint
of HIPAA regulations.

00:48:49.648 --> 00:48:51.440
DIANE SHADER SMITH:
And I have to tell you,

00:48:51.440 --> 00:48:54.750
there are so many more
issues that have come up.

00:48:54.750 --> 00:48:57.650
I'll give you a three
sentence example.

00:48:57.650 --> 00:49:01.910
They kick parents out of the
ICU at shift change because

00:49:01.910 --> 00:49:04.340
of HIPAA, and they
want to make sure

00:49:04.340 --> 00:49:06.440
that, when they're doing
their bedside reporting,

00:49:06.440 --> 00:49:09.950
that patient confidentiality
is not being--

00:49:09.950 --> 00:49:12.540
so Mallory had her transplant.

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:14.485
She had made us
promise and swear,

00:49:14.485 --> 00:49:16.610
up and down in every
direction, that we would never

00:49:16.610 --> 00:49:17.515
ever leave her alone.

00:49:17.515 --> 00:49:19.640
And Mark and Jack and I
rotated, because he flew in

00:49:19.640 --> 00:49:21.360
and Mark was there
at that point.

00:49:21.360 --> 00:49:23.360
And I was at home sleeping,
and Jack was at home

00:49:23.360 --> 00:49:25.400
sleeping in the apartment,
and Mark was on duty,

00:49:25.400 --> 00:49:29.572
and the nurses refused
to do the report bedside.

00:49:29.572 --> 00:49:31.280
And Mallory was
ventilated at that point,

00:49:31.280 --> 00:49:35.150
and sedated and drugged out,
and they refused to do report.

00:49:35.150 --> 00:49:36.450
They wanted to kick him out.

00:49:36.450 --> 00:49:37.722
It became a big brouhaha.

00:49:37.722 --> 00:49:39.680
And Mallory scribbled on
a thing, Dad, it's OK.

00:49:39.680 --> 00:49:40.263
You can leave.

00:49:40.263 --> 00:49:42.320
I want them to do the
reporting bedside.

00:49:42.320 --> 00:49:44.870
I want to hear it and then
they'll get you and come back.

00:49:44.870 --> 00:49:47.265
I was home asleep and
about, apparently,

00:49:47.265 --> 00:49:49.640
15 minutes after this incident
happened, the phone rings.

00:49:49.640 --> 00:49:51.530
I will never forget this moment.

00:49:51.530 --> 00:49:53.870
And I'm in my half
exhausted sleep

00:49:53.870 --> 00:49:55.050
and I say, oh, it's Mallory.

00:49:55.050 --> 00:49:56.120
Why is Mallory calling me?

00:49:56.120 --> 00:49:56.450
Uh-oh.

00:49:56.450 --> 00:49:57.120
What's wrong?

00:49:57.120 --> 00:49:58.190
And I answer the phone
and I hear this--

00:49:58.190 --> 00:50:00.600
[BANGING ON LECTERN]----
at the top of my lungs.

00:50:00.600 --> 00:50:02.940
And I knew instantly there
was a problem and I knew--

00:50:02.940 --> 00:50:04.207
I don't know how I knew--

00:50:04.207 --> 00:50:05.290
she was hitting the phone.

00:50:05.290 --> 00:50:06.350
It was just so obvious to me.

00:50:06.350 --> 00:50:07.260
I screamed for Jack.

00:50:07.260 --> 00:50:08.050
I handed him the phone.

00:50:08.050 --> 00:50:08.842
I say, talk to her.

00:50:08.842 --> 00:50:10.050
Don't stop talking.

00:50:10.050 --> 00:50:10.620
Keep talking.

00:50:10.620 --> 00:50:11.460
Let her hear your voice.

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:11.960
Soothe her.

00:50:11.960 --> 00:50:12.630
Comfort her.

00:50:12.630 --> 00:50:16.680
I call Mark, screaming like
a crazy, raging lunatic.

00:50:16.680 --> 00:50:18.720
He goes back in and
we go racing over,

00:50:18.720 --> 00:50:21.000
and the bottom line
is, this is the policy.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:25.140
If you Google ICU shift
change, you will see,

00:50:25.140 --> 00:50:27.210
it comes up in big
letters that it's

00:50:27.210 --> 00:50:30.330
customary protocol to ask
the families and loved

00:50:30.330 --> 00:50:30.990
ones to leave.

00:50:30.990 --> 00:50:32.592
Now the stupidest thing of all.

00:50:32.592 --> 00:50:34.800
When is the time that the
patient is paying the least

00:50:34.800 --> 00:50:35.802
attention to you?

00:50:35.802 --> 00:50:36.510
I mean the nurse.

00:50:36.510 --> 00:50:38.670
The nurse is paying the
least attention to you

00:50:38.670 --> 00:50:41.490
supposedly when they're
engaged in passing the notes

00:50:41.490 --> 00:50:42.858
from the night to the day.

00:50:42.858 --> 00:50:44.400
And so what that
means is at the time

00:50:44.400 --> 00:50:46.025
they're actually
talking to each other,

00:50:46.025 --> 00:50:48.390
how could they be paying
attention to their patient?

00:50:48.390 --> 00:50:51.893
So this is one issue
that is not in my speech,

00:50:51.893 --> 00:50:54.060
but it's something that I
feel really strongly about

00:50:54.060 --> 00:50:55.530
and it's something I
want to work hard for.

00:50:55.530 --> 00:50:57.610
But if I were you and I had
a kid that ever ended up

00:50:57.610 --> 00:50:59.060
in the hospital,
I would make sure

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:00.810
that you dealt with
that issue right away.

00:51:00.810 --> 00:51:01.470
HIPAA waiver.

00:51:01.470 --> 00:51:02.550
Obvious duh.

00:51:02.550 --> 00:51:04.345
You've signed the HIPAA waiver.

00:51:04.345 --> 00:51:06.220
You're allowed to speak
in front of your son.

00:51:06.220 --> 00:51:08.250
But we had one,
Mallory had signed it,

00:51:08.250 --> 00:51:10.992
and still they kicked Mark out.

00:51:10.992 --> 00:51:11.820
KEVIN: Great.

00:51:11.820 --> 00:51:14.880
Thank you, Diane, Jack,
and Mark for this talk,

00:51:14.880 --> 00:51:16.088
and thank you all for coming.

00:51:16.088 --> 00:51:16.880
MARK SMITH: Thanks.

00:51:16.880 --> 00:51:18.170
DIANE SHADER SMITH: Thank you.

